Week 2: What is theory?

Week 3: The Politics of Authorship

  • Traditional view: meaning = authors intention
  • What if meaning lies with the audience?
  • AAA games: collaborative authorship & distributed creativity
  • Who gets credit? Visible leads vs. invisible contributors
  • Industry uses authorship for branding & prestige
  • Goal: rethink authorship in production, play & creativity

Week 3Preparation

Reading: Staiger, J. (2003). Authorship approaches. In D. Gerstner & J. Staiger (eds.), Authorship and Film, pp. 2757.

Task

  • Find media about an artist (author, filmmaker, showrunner, animator, designer, game producer, or musician).
  • Could be a review, interview, retrospective, or analysis.
  • What values, assumptions, or beliefs are expressed about the role of the author/auteur?
    • Life influencing work?
    • Directors role in film?
    • Creators identity shaping evaluation?

LO1

Jason Rohrer

Week 4: Media Messages and Audiences

Media Messages and Audiences

  • Howaudiencesread& interpretmediamessages
  • Semioticsofmedia: signs, symbols& meaning-making
  • Stuart HallsEncoding/Decoding:
    • Media textsareencodedwithintendedmeanings
    • Audiencesdecodethemdifferently
    • Influencedbybackgrounds, ideologies, experiences
  • Marshall McLuhan
    • Medium isthemessage

Week 4 Preparation

  • Reading: Hall, S. (1973/1999). Encoding/Decoding. In S. During (ed.), The Cultural Studies Reader. Routledge, pp. 507517.

Task

  • How do cultural perspectives, values, beliefs, and identities shape the way media is made and understood?
  • Suggest media examples to analyse with Halls Encoding/Decodingmodel.
  • interpreting media just as important as creating it for understanding its impact? (LO1)

LO1

Week 5: Globalisationand Polycentrism

  • Globalisationasan emptysignifier multiple meanings
  • Key terms: global, local, glocalisation
  • Media & power: hierarchiesacrossglobal platformsand cultures
  • Eurocentrism: dominanceofWestern perspectivesin mediarepresentation

Week 5 Preparation

  • Reading: Iwabuchi, K. (2002). From Western gaze to global gaze: Japanese cultural presence in Asia. In D. Crane, N. Kawashima & K. Kawasaki (eds.), Global Culture. Routledge, pp. 256274.
  • Task
  • Choose a global media product or franchise.
  • What makes it global?
  • Apply Iwabuchis idea of the culturally odorless product:
    • Does your example conceal its national origins?
    • what extent does it fit this concept?

LO1

Week 6: Fandom and Fan Cultures

  • Fans as a key site of academic study
  • Reveal the complex ties between audience, text & consumption
  • Fans engage in creative, subversive practices with screen media
  • Fandom shows audiences as active, not passive
  • Highlights tensions:
    • Exploitation by cultural industries
    • Toxicity in online fan spaces
    • Contradictory responses of devoted audiences

Week 6: Preparation

  • Reading: Kirkland, E. (2020). Contextualising the bronies: cult, quality, subculture and the contradictions of contemporary fandom. Journal of Popular Television, 8(1), 87104.
  • Task
  • Jenkins (1992): fan culture is subversive, challenging norms of gender, sexuality, race, and taste.
  • Find a fan-created media examplethat is more progressive, diverse, or inclusive than its source franchise.
  • ready to present and defend your choice in class. (LO2)

LO2

Week 7: Taste, Class and Cultural Value

  • What counts as quality media is tied to class, gender, race, age, aesthetics & technology
  • Historic debates: art vs. popular culture across painting, literature, film, TV & digital media
  • Questioning good vs. bad culture judgments about makers & audiences
  • Why have videogames been excluded from galleries/museums?
  • Struggles of game designers & artists for recognition

Week 7 Preparation

  • Reading: Jenkins, H. (2005). Games, the new lively art. In J. Rassens & J. Goldstein (eds.), Handbook of Computer Game Studies. MIT Press, pp. 175189.
  • Task
  • Choose a popular media example (film, TV, game, music, video, website).
  • What knowledge does the audience need to fully appreciate it?
  • Does it assume a particular gender, sexuality, class, ethnicity, or subculture?
  • How does its language include some / exclude others?
  • Does it reinforce or challenge normative attitudes? (LO2)
